slides.title: Actortype
slides.text:
This map shows the different types of actors in the network. The largest governmental actor is (perhaps unsurprisingly) the National Institutes of Health. The largest NGO in the network is CHADD, a "national non-profit [...] organization providing education, advocacy and support for individuals with ADHD", and founded in 1987.
Some clarification of the color codes:
Treatment: Clinics etc. offering psychiatric evaluation, diagnosis and treatment for children with ADHD (and others).
Education: Special schools and programs for children with ADHD (and related disorders).
Professional: Academic articles about ADHD. If you read the page "Expertise" on this website - this is where we find the highest level of scientific expertise.

slides.title: Actortype
slides.text: As can be seen from the color codes, the little bouquet sprouting from CHADD consists mainly of websites offering diagnosis and treatment, and coaching for children and other people with ADHD.

slides.title: Domaintype
slides.text: The map above shows the websites according to domain type. In some ways, this is 'just' another way of showing the types of actors present in the network.

slides.title: Definition of ADHD
slides.text: This map shows the ways in which different actors define ADHD. However, we have chosen to group most of these definitions together under appropriate headlines because there are a surprising number of words and terms that are used to describe ADHD. This means that "Disorder" also covers those who talk about ADHD as a specific kind of disorder, e.g. "brain disorder", "neurological disorder" etc. The headline "Fake" is given to definitions such as "fictitious disease" and "invention".

slides.title: ADHD attributed to
slides.text:
This map shows a slightly different way of defining ADHD. It is colored according to the criteria "What is ADHD attributed to?" and/or "What does ADHD primarily affect?" Many websites only use the word "disorder", but some specify that it has to do with neurology (or -biology, -development, or -physiology), behavior, etc.
Regrettably, only the most common labels have managed to get their own color.

slides.title: View of ADHD
slides.text: This map is perhaps the most important and interesting one in our project, even though it only has three labels. What we have called "Pro" covers those websites that clearly acknowledge ADHD as a real, valid psychiatric diagnosis, and rarely-if-ever mention the potential problems with the diagnostics of this type of disorder. The websites labelled "Semi", however, acknowledge ADHD as valid, but show concern that it is being misdiagnosed and/or overdiagnosed in some cases. The "Con" label covers those who do not think that ADHD (or even mental illness in generel) is 'real' at all.

slides.title: View of ADHD
slides.text:
It is quite clear that the "Pro" side is by far the largest in numbers and apparent importance (if measured by size/number of links). There are multiple possible explanations for this. First of all, it is important to remember that these maps only map the online part of the issue - the exclusively 'off-line' opinions of individuals and groups don't show.
On the other hand, the "Pro" actors are the ones who have a personal and/or financial interest in ADHD being considered a valid diagnosis. This combined with official/government opinion being "Pro", it might not be surprising that this group is the largest and loudest.

slides.title: View of ADHD
slides.text: Here's something interesting: Find the red dot "Behaviorismandmentalhealth. This is a blog by a retired psychologist named Philip Hickey. This website is labelled "Con" for very good reasons, no gray areas here. But notice that he links to both "Semi" and "Pro" actors, like the NIH. This illustrates another important point about web mapping; a link doesn't tell us why it's there. Actors often link to the websites they agree with, but not always - sometimes a link on a page is accompanied by a critique (or even an insult).
